HETEROPHYIASIS - PHILLIPINES (NEGROS ISLAND) (02)
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Wed 27 Sep 2006
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: Gideononline [edited]
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>

The following species of heterophyid trematodes are known to infest
humans in the Philippines:
_Carneophallus_ (_Heterophyes brevicaeca_, _Spelotrema brevicaeca_) -
acquired from raw shrimp.
_Centrocestus formsanus_, a parasite of rats, cats, dogs, chickens
and ducks - acquired from freshwater fish and frogs.
_Diorchitrema pseudocirratum_, _Haplorchis pumilio_, a parasite of
cats and dogs - acquired from ingestion of freshwater fish.
_Haplorchis taichui_ - acquired from freshwater fish. 36.0 percent of
persons in San Isidro, Compostella Valley are infested (2000).
_Haplorchis vanissimus_, _Haplorchis yokogawi_, a parasite of cats
and dogs - acquired from ingestion of shrimp and mullet.
_Hetrerophyopsis continua_, a parasite of cats - acquired from fish
(_Mugil cephalus_, _Mugil affinis_, _Larus argentatus_, _Cyprinus carpio_).
_Procerovum calderoni_, a parasite of cats and dogs - acquired from
fish. _Stellantchasmus falcatus_, a parasite of cats, dogs and birds
- acquired from fish (_Mugil cephalus_).
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
